John Edward: Language skills essential for world citizens
The independent schools in Scotland have an excellent position of service in the field of academic excellence, and this continued in 2018 with another set of excellent exam results, as well as individual and collective success in sport, art, music and other initiatives of the whole community.
With more than 30,000 pupils in Scotland, these schools, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), aim to provide the best service to their pupils and parents.
Independent schools strive to prepare their students for further and higher education, their chosen career and their place as world citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a tailor-made school curriculum, we see that modern languages remain popular and desired subjects in excellent schools.
Nelson Mandela said: “If you talk to someone in a language he understands, you reach his head.
If you talk to him in his own language, you reach his heart."
This is a powerful reminder that we can not only trust in English if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From this year's recent exam results, we can derive that languages are top of the ranking, with the highest drop rates within independent schools.
A total of 68 per cent of the students studying foreign languages achieved a high score.
The data collected from 74 schools associated with SCIS show that 72 per cent of students achieved a high score ('A') in Mandarin, while 72 per cent of students in German, 69 per cent of students in French and 63 per cent of students in Spanish also achieved an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as essential skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are now valued as specialist choice as STEM subjects (science, technology, technology and mathematics) in independent school programmes and elsewhere.
According to employers, a survey by the UK Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 showed that 17% of the traffic jams to fill vacancies were attributed to a lack of language skills.
Language skills are thus becoming increasingly important in preparing young people for their future career.
Now that more and more jobs require language skills, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the career that a person chooses, if he has learned a second language, he will have a real advantage in the future with such a skill for life.
Communicating directly with people from abroad automatically gives a multilingual person an advantage on competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75% were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to hold a conversation. French was the only language out of the 10%, with a total of 15%.
This is why investing in language education is now important for today's children.
Several languages can speak, especially those of emerging economies, will offer children a better chance of finding a meaningful job.
In Scotland schools themselves choose which languages they teach.
A number of schools will focus on the more classic modern languages, while other schools will teach languages that are most important for the United Kingdom when they are looking forward to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child’s interest is, there will always be different languages to choose from in independent schools, with teachers specialised in this field.
Scottish independent schools are working to provide a learning environment that prepares children and gives them the skills needed to succeed, regardless of the future.
It cannot be denied at the moment that languages in a global business environment remain vital for the future of the country, so this needs to be reflected in education.
Modern languages should in fact be regarded as 'international communication skills'.
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
We have to do it.
