A new course at Harvard University this year will make sure that all students get more sleep, in an attempt to combat the growing macho culture in which it seems cool to study through the night and drink a lot of caffeine.
One professor found that the students of the world's largest university often have no idea of the basic principles to care for themselves.
Charles Czeisler, Professor of Sleep Medicine at Harvard Medical School, a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, set up the course. As far as he knows, this is unique in the USA.
He got the idea to start the course after giving a speech on the influence of sleep failure on learning.
'At the end of my speech, a girl came to me saying, 'Why do I get to hear this in my last year?'
She said that no one ever told her how important sleep is, what surprised me', he said to The Telegraph.
The course, which is organised for the first time this year, explains to the students the basic principles of how good sleep habits help to improve academic and athletic performance and how they also promote their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, said the university decided to organize the course when it was determined that students had a severe sleep deficiency during the week.
The course lasts one hour and includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one of the parts, the students see an image of a dormitory, where they click on coffee cups, curtains, exercise equipment and books to learn more about the effects of caffeine and light and how sports performance is affected by sleep failure, and the importance of a routine sleeping experience.
In another section, participants will learn how long-term sleep failure increases the risk of a heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
Using a map of the campus, with interactive icons, participants are encouraged to reflect on their daily routine.
“We know that this will not change the behaviour of the students immediately.
But we think they have the right to know all of this, just as people have the right to know what the consequences of the choice of cigarettes will have on their health, Czeisler added.
The culture of pride at night still exists, he says, and because of modern technology and the increasing pressure on students, sleep shortages are an ever greater problem.
Care for adequate sleep, of good quality, must be the student's 'secret weapon' to fight stress, fatigue and fear, he said, and even to avoid weight gain, because sleep loss makes the brain give them a constant sense of hunger.
