HIV/AIDS: China reports an increase of 14% in new cases
China reports an increase of 14% in the number of Chinese people with HIV and AIDS.
Health authorities say that more than 820,000 people have been affected by it in the country.
Only in the second quarter of 2018, 40,000 new cases were reported.
In the vast majority of new cases, the diseases were passed on through sex, which was not the case before.
In the past, HIV has spread rapidly in some parts of China through transfusions of infected blood.
But the number of people this way is almost zero, Chinese health officials said at a conference in Yunnan Province.
However, compared to the same period last year, the number of people with HIV and AIDS in China has increased by 100,000.
The transfer of HIV via sex is an acute problem in the Chinese LGBT community.
Homosexuality has been no longer criminalized in China since 1997, but discrimination against LGBT people is said to be widespread.
According to studies, the conservative values of the country estimated that 70 to 90% of men having sex with men would eventually marry a woman.
Often the diseases are transmitted by inadequate protection in sexual relations in these relationships.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has promised universal access to HIV medication as part of its efforts to address the problem.
