National Trust listens to the secret life of bats
New research carried out on a estate in the Scottish Highlands seeks to reveal how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
It is hoped that the findings will shed light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and contribute to future conservation activities.
The study carried out by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland follows the ordinary and small dwarf bat, the brown large ear bat and the water bat at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording equipment is placed at key locations around the estate to follow the activities of the bats throughout the season.
NTS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile investigations using hand detectors.
Expert sound analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of the clocks of the bat and what kind of thing does.
Then a map of the habitat and a report are produced to make a detailed picture on the landscape scale of their behaviour.
Rob Dewar, Nature Conservation Advisor to the NTS, hopes that the results will show which areas of the habitat are most important for bats and how they are used by the species.
This information will help to determine the benefits of habitat management, such as the creation of pasture fields and how best to maintain forests for bats and similar species.
Fleeen populations in Scotland and the rest of the UK have declined significantly in the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development activities that affect sleeping places and the loss of habitat.
Wind turbines and lightning can also pose a risk, such as fly-catchers and certain chemical treatments of building materials and house tax attacks.
Bats aren't really blind.
However, their nocturnal hunting habits make their ears more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching a prey.
They use an advanced echo location technique to determine the position of insects and obstacles in their flight route.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, takes bats very seriously.
The NTS has ten trained experts, who regularly investigate, inspect sleeping places and sometimes rescue actions.
The organization has even established the first and only reserve for bats in Scotland at the estate Threave in Dumfries and Galloway, where eight of the ten species live in Scotland.
Landscape manager David Thompson says the estate is the ideal territory for bats.
"Here in Threave we have a great environment for bats," he said.
"We have the old buildings, very old trees and the right habitats.
But there is so much not yet known about bats and therefore the work we do here and in other locations will help us better understand what they need to thrive."
He stressed the importance of monitoring bats before maintenance work is carried out, as the possible unconscious destruction of a sleeping place could lead to the death of 400 female bats and their young, possibly eliminating a full local population.
Bats are a protected animal species and it is illegal to kill them, to fall into trouble or to disturb them or to destroy their sleeping places.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish official for the Bat Conservation Trust, has asked the public to make a contribution to help.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats and of many of our species, we just don't know how their populations are."
