Foreign buyers will have to pay higher fees when they buy a house in the UK and the extra yield is used to help the homeless, Theresa May will announce today.
This action is seen as an attempt to neutralize the success of Jeremy Corbyn that attracts young voters with promises to ensure more affordable homes and to tell stories to many earners.
The increase in the lay-offs is imposed on persons and firms who do not pay tax in the UK, where the extra income is put in an attempt by the government to combat homeless people.
The surcharge, which comes on top of the current leases, including the higher levels introduced two years ago for second houses and houses bought for rent, may amount to 3%.
The Ministry of Finance expects to raise up to £120 million per year in this way.
It is estimated that 13% of new construction in London is bought by people who do not live in the UK, which drives prices up and makes it difficult for starters to get a foot on the home charger.
Many prosperous areas in the country, especially in the capital, have become practically 'spook cities' because of the high number of foreign buyers spending most of the time outside the country.
This new policy comes just a few weeks after Boris Johnson had argued for a reduction in the layoff to help young people buy their first home.
He accused large construction companies of keeping prices high by buying land and not using it, and he called on May to abolish quotas on affordable houses to restore the 'housing scandal' in Britain.
Corbyn has announced a remarkable series of housing reforms, including rental ceilings and an end to expulsion 'without negligence'.
He also wants to give local authorities more opportunities to build new houses.
May said: "Last year I said that I wanted to spend my time as Prime Minister on the restoration of the British Dream that life will be better for every new generation.
And that means that our defective housing market needs to be restored.
Britain will always be open to people who want to live, work and build a life here.
However, it cannot be that it is as easy for people who do not live in the UK and for foreign companies to buy houses here as it is for hard-working British residents.
For too many people, the dream of owning a house has become too vague a dream and the humiliation of life without a roof over the head is already real."
